The need to fit in and the conviction that one is right in one's peers both contribute to the phenomenon of conformity. The need to fit in with other people persists despite any doubts about the accuracy of the information. Group size, agreement among members, and the presence of an authoritative person are all important predictors of conformity. The presence of a confident leader or authority figure relates to the perceived knowledge or status of the person leading the group, while group size refers to the number of persons in the group and the amount of agreement among group members. 